{"cursor":"7534","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox company\n| name = Pearson Yachts logo = former type = Public company type = Subsidiary\n| traded_as = industry = Sailboat Builder fate = Sold in Bankruptcy predecessor\n| = successor = foundation = Bristol, Rhode Island, United States () founder =\n| defunct = location_city = Portsmouth, Rhode Island location_country = United\n| States locations = \n| area_served = key_people = products = Sailboats production = services =\n| revenue = operating_income = net_income = assets = equity = owner =\n| num_employees = parent = Grumman Allied Industries divisions = subsid =\n| homepage =  footnotes = bodystyle =\n}}\n\n\n'Pearson Yachts' was a leading manufacturer of fiberglass sailboats from the\nlate 1950s till the late 1980s. Pearson Yachts was founded by cousins Clinton\nand Everett Pearson, in a small garage located in Bristol, Rhode Island in\n1956. The company was one of earliest fiberglass\nsailboat manufacturers. The Carl Alberg designed Triton 28 launched at the New\nYork Boat Show in January 1959 began the modern era of fiberglass sailboat\nproduction. They experienced tremendous growth\nthrough the 1960s and 1970s producing a wide array of sail boats most of them\ndesigned by Bill Shaw. For Nearly 50 years Pearson Yachts built premium-branded\nsailboats, as well as Etchells raceboats, thousands of J/Boats, a fleet of 44-\nfoot offshore Sail Training Craft for the United States Naval Academy, and many\nothers. After changing ownership throughout the 1980s Pearson Yachts was sold in\nthe bankruptcy of Grumman Allied Industries in 1991. Since the companies\nfounding Everett Pearson maintained ownership of the Pearson Yachts name and\ncurrently USWatercraft formerly known as The Pearson Marine Group holds rights\nto the name.\n","linknr":145,"url":"Pearson_Yachts","recorded":1374785830,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Pearson_Yachts&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Pearson_Yachts&action=edit","